# migrated from tests/cases/gen_weight.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test gen_weight]
# gen111 (D-prop1 step 2): the decoder's choice ranking is itself KB knowledge.
# The generation loop (gen36-42) interpolates trigram and bigram evidence to pick
# the next word; gen111 moves the interpolation COEFFICIENTS out of hardcoded C
# into editable weight(trigram, N) / weight(bigram, N) facts. Editing the policy
# (a fact) changes which continuation wins — the ranking lives in the KB, not the
# code (DESIGN.md D6: shrink the hardcoded C, grow behaviour as knowledge).

# Teach two contexts that DISAGREE: the bigram "apple ->" favours juice (seen
# twice) over pie (once), but the trigram "red apple ->" has only ever seen pie.
> learn sequence: red apple pie
< Learned 2 transition(s).
> learn sequence: green apple juice
< Learned 2 transition(s).
> learn sequence: green apple juice
< Learned 2 transition(s).
# Default policy: the trigram context dominates, so "red apple ___" -> pie, even
# though "juice" has the stronger bigram count.
> say red
< red apple pie
# Now EDIT the policy as knowledge: tell the decoder to ignore trigram context.
> set trigram weight to 0
< Ok, trigram weight is now 0.
# Same seed, same data — but the choice flips, because the bigram majority now
# decides. Generation behaviour was steered by editing a fact, not the C.
> say red
< red apple juice
